04735nam a22007215i 9780813569499DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152015nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2014030635  a97808135694997 a10.36019/97808135694992doi  a(DE-B1597)526314  a(OCoLC)916450657  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aHV9304b.L395 2015 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a365/.609732231 aLeigey, Margaret E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Forgotten Men :bServing a Life without Parole Sentence /cMargaret E. Leigey. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (242 p.) :b3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical Issues in Crime and Society00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: Death by Incarceration -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. The Rise in the Permanently Incarcerated -- t2. The Forgotten -- t3. The Pains of Permanent Imprisonment -- t4. Coping with Permanent Incarceration -- t5. Growing Old in Prison -- t6. Forgotten No More -- tAppendix A: Pseudonyms and Demographics of Respondents -- tAppendix B: Researching the Forgotten -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tCases -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aToday there are approximately fifty thousand prisoners in American prisons serving life without parole, having been found guilty of crimes ranging from murder and rape to burglary, carjacking, and drug offences. In The Forgotten Men, criminologist Margaret E. Leigey provides an insightful account of a group of aging inmates imprisoned for at least twenty years, with virtually no chance of release. These men make up one of the most marginalized segments of the contemporary U.S. prison population. Considered too dangerous for rehabilitation, ignored by prison administrators, and overlooked by courts disinclined to review such sentences, these prisoners grow increasingly cut off from family and the outside world. Drawing on in-depth interviews with twenty-five such prisoners, Leigey gives voice to these extremely marginalized inmates and offers a look at how they struggle to cope. She reveals, for instance, that the men believe that permanent incarceration is as inhumane as capital punishment, calling life without parole “the hard death penalty.” Indeed, after serving two decades in prison, some wished that they had received the death penalty instead. Leigey also recounts the ways in which the prisoners attempt to construct meaningful lives inside the bleak environment where they will almost certainly live out their lives. Every state in the union (except Alaska) has the life-without-parole sentencing option, despite its controversial nature and its staggering cost to the taxpayer. The Forgotten Men provides a much-needed analysis of the policies behind life-without-parole sentencing, arguing that such sentences are overused and lead to serious financial and ethical dilemmas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCapital punishmentzUnited States. 0aLife imprisonmentzUnited States. 0aParolezUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066615140uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081356949940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813569499423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813569499.jpg  a978-3-11-066615-1  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENG